      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Spear-phishing attackers often use psychological manipulation to trick employees into divulging sensitive information or clicking on malicious links. They may use social engineering tactics such as building rapport, using the employee's name, referencing a shared interest or company event, or even threatening to close accounts if immediate action isn't taken. These tactics can create a false sense of familiarity, urgency, or curiosity, causing employees to bypass their usual caution and discipline. By highlighting these tactics, you can help employees understand that spear-phishing is as much a psychological game as it is a technical one.",
      "source": "target",
